This problem was asked to me an year back in an On-campus interview, and I wasn't not able to solve it without using extra space. Well I can now. 
We are given that the nums1 array can accomodate the elements of the nums2 easily so we simply pick element from the end sides of both these array and compare their values and insert them into the nums1 array. 
The first case is basically if the first array(nums1) doesn't contain any element, then we simply insert the second array(nums2) inside nums1, the second case is if nums2 doesn't contain any element then we do nothing as the nums1 would simply justify the answer.
<br>
<b> Things to remember </b>
<ul>
<li>We are given that nums1 can accomodate nums2, if it is given that nums1 cannot then simply insert 0's at the end of the array and this will work just fine.</li>
<li>Running from the end gives us privilege more than running the pointers from the start.</li>
</ul>

<b> Java Code </b>
```
public void merge(int[] nums1, int m, int[] nums2, int n) {
        int i = m-1, j = n- 1, k = m + n - 1;
        while(i>=0 && j>=0){
            if(nums1[i] > nums2[j]){
                nums1[k--] = nums1[i--];
            }else{
                nums1[k--] = nums2[j--];
            }
        }
		// this while loop is for the condition when nums1 doesn't contain any element.
        while(j>=0){
            nums1[k--] = nums2[j--];
        }
    }
```

