		Example taken:  
						-> a: [1, 2, 3, 0, 0, 0]
						-> b: [2, 5, 6]
Steps: 

1. Reverse both the arrays.
	-> Then it would be like this: 
				a: ``` [0, 0, 0, 3, 2, 1] ```
				b: ``` [6, 5, 2] ```

2. Take three pointers: 
	i) **i** pointing to the first participating element from **a** // Here it is 3
	ii) **j** pointing to the first participating element from **b** // Here it is 6
	iii) **ind** pointing to the first empty space in **a** to be filled // Here it is ind = 0

3. Then iterate until **i** reach the end of **a** OR **j** reach the end of **b**:
	i) Simply put the bigger element on index "**ind**" in **a** and increase the corresponding **i** OR **j**

4. At last just put the remaining elements of **b** into **a**.

```
void merge(vector<int>& a, int n, vector<int>& b, int m) 
    {
		// Reversing the arrays
		reverse(a.begin(), a.end());
        reverse(b.begin(), b.end());

		// Taking pointers
        int i = m, j = 0, ind = 0;

        while(i < (n + m) && j < m)
        {
			// Inserting the bigger element into "a" at "ind"
			if(a[i] > b[j])
            {
                a[ind] = a[i];
                i++;
            }
            else 
            {
                a[ind] = b[j];
                j++;
            }
            ind++;
        }

		//Inserting the remaining elements
        while(j < m) 
        {
            a[ind++] = b[j++];
        }        

		//Reversing the array "a" to get the final result
        reverse(a.begin(), a.end());
    }
