solutions.content:
The solution is actually looping once on `nums1` array from its end (which is empty) to the start. 
On each iteration, we decide whether to copy an element from `nums1` or from `nums2` (starting from their end and using `index1` and `index2` to keep pointing to the remaining elements of each array). 
It's better to start inserting elements into the back of the array of `nums1`, where there's empty space...

Note that there's no need to continue looping after running out of elements in `nums2`, since `nums1` is already sorted.

```
// Space complexity: O(1) - no additional space
// Time complexity: O(n+m)

/**
 Do not return anything, modify nums1 in-place instead.
 */
function merge(nums1: number[], m: number, nums2: number[], n: number): void {
    let index1 = m-1;
    let index2 = n-1;

    for (let i = n+m-1; i >= 0 && index2 >= 0; i--){
        const num1 = nums1[index1];
        const num2 = nums2[index2]

        if (index1 >= 0 && num1 > num2){
            nums1[i] = num1;
            index1--;
        } else {
            nums1[i] = num2;
            index2--;
        }
    }
};
```

